   "source": [
    "# Mean Functions\n",
    "\n",
    "In the previous chapter we talked about [kernels](kernels.ipynb). If you go back and look at the plots, you may notice that even in the plots without any data, where we just look at $f$ samples, the $f$ samples are kind of close to 0. Why is that? The kernels define what kinds of shape $f$ can take, but not where the function is; a mean function defines where. In the section on kernels we didn't specify a mean function, and the default mean function is constant 0, which explains why, by default, $f$ samples will be close to 0."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "739713a6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As usual we will start with some necessary imports:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "1fd6a1cd",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:31.159243Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:31.158984Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:35.725355Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:35.724595Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import tensorflow as tf\n",
    "from check_shapes import inherit_check_shapes\n",
    "\n",
    "import gpflow"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f29e7214",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And a helper function to visualise our models:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "78f17cc7",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:35.728947Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:35.728314Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:35.741828Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:35.740626Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_model(\n",
    "    model: gpflow.models.GPModel,\n",
    "    *,\n",
    "    min_x: float,\n",
    "    max_x: float,\n",
    "    optimise: bool = True,\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    _, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    if optimise:\n",
    "        opt = gpflow.optimizers.Scipy()\n",
    "        opt.minimize(model.training_loss, model.trainable_variables)\n",
    "\n",
    "    Xplot = np.linspace(min_x, max_x, 300)[:, None]\n",
    "\n",
    "    f_mean, f_var = model.predict_f(Xplot, full_cov=False)\n",
    "    f_lower = f_mean - 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "    f_upper = f_mean + 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax.hlines(0.0, min_x, max_x, colors=\"black\", linestyles=\"dotted\", alpha=0.3)\n",
    "    ax.scatter(X, Y, color=\"black\")\n",
    "    (mean_line,) = ax.plot(Xplot, f_mean, \"-\")\n",
    "    color = mean_line.get_color()\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xplot, f_lower, lw=0.1, color=color)\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xplot, f_upper, lw=0.1, color=color)\n",
    "    ax.fill_between(\n",
    "        Xplot[:, 0], f_lower[:, 0], f_upper[:, 0], color=color, alpha=0.1\n",
    "    )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f09ab698",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Mean reversion\n",
    "\n",
    "Observe:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "bb98daff",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:35.745692Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:35.744919Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:38.432555Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:38.423640Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "X = np.array([[0.0], [0.1], [0.2], [0.3], [0.4]])\n",
    "Y = np.array([[2.0], [1.7], [1.6], [1.7], [2.0]])\n",
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR((X, Y), kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern32())\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-0.1, max_x=4.1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e463e862",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As we move away from the data our predictions converge towards 0. Basically, as we move away from the data, the model does not know what to predict, and will revert towards the mean function. This is called [\"mean reversion\"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_toward_the_mean), and this is the primary use case where having a reasonable mean function can help. In the areas where we have plenty of data, we don't need a mean function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a9ef5d5a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setting a mean function\n",
    "\n",
    "Our models generally take a `mean_function` object that you can set to any instance of [gpflow.functions.MeanFunction](../../api/gpflow/functions/index.rst#gpflow.functions.MeanFunction). See our [API documentation](../../api/gpflow/functions/index.rst) for a full list of built-in mean functions.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the above example I happen to know that our data is a quadratic function, so let us try setting our mean function to a 2nd degree polynomial:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "df4c1d42",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:38.436167Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:38.435807Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:39.239345Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:39.238227Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern32(),\n",
    "    mean_function=gpflow.functions.Polynomial(2),\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-0.1, max_x=4.1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bf8795cd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Our model now fits our mean function to the data without any noise, and happily extrapolates the quadratic function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "76e0dc2e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Interactions with the kernel\n",
    "\n",
    "The shape of $f$ relative to the mean function is determined by the kernel.\n",
    "\n",
    "So, if we have a linear mean function:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "6f94ada8",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:39.244029Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:39.243526Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:39.913214Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:39.912530Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "X = np.array([[0.0], [0.1], [0.2], [0.3], [0.4]])\n",
    "Y = np.array([[1.0], [1.3], [1.2], [1.5], [1.4]])\n",
    "\n",
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Constant(),\n",
    "    mean_function=gpflow.functions.Linear(),\n",
    "    noise_variance=1e-3,\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-1.0, max_x=1.4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b64d9f36",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And a periodic kernel:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "7a302cd0",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:39.915938Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:39.915616Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:40.980638Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:40.979942Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Periodic(gpflow.kernels.Matern32(), period=0.2),\n",
    "    mean_function=gpflow.functions.Zero(),\n",
    "    noise_variance=1e-3,\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-1.0, max_x=1.4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6da014c9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And combine them, we get a period around a line:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "03bf87de",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:40.985314Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:40.984971Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:41.701508Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:41.700642Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Periodic(gpflow.kernels.Matern32(), period=0.2),\n",
    "    mean_function=gpflow.functions.Linear(),\n",
    "    noise_variance=1e-3,\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-1.0, max_x=1.4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "32e5e9c0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Kernels versus mean functions\n",
    "\n",
    "There is some overlap in what you can achieve with kernels and mean functions. If you have some external reason to expect your data to have a particular shape, we recommend you use that as a mean function. For example, you may be modelling a physical system where you have closed-form (physics) equations available that describes the system. However, if you do not have an external reason to pick a particular mean function we generally recommend you work on picking a good kernel, instead of setting a mean function. A good kernel will be better at \"letting the data speak for itself\", whereas if you set a bad mean function, you can get misleading predictions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "39f0548e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Custom mean functions\n",
    "\n",
    "It is easy enough to create a custom mean function. You must extend the [gpflow.functions.MeanFunction](../../api/gpflow/functions/index.rst#gpflow.functions.MeanFunction) class, which only requires you to implement a `__call__` method. For example:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "54fbfe6a",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:41.705609Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:41.705274Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:42.312166Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:42.310923Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "class SineMeanFunction(gpflow.functions.MeanFunction):\n",
    "    @inherit_check_shapes\n",
    "    def __call__(self, X: gpflow.base.TensorType) -> tf.Tensor:\n",
    "        return tf.sin(X)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "X = np.zeros((0, 1))\n",
    "Y = np.zeros((0, 1))\n",
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern12(),\n",
    "    mean_function=SineMeanFunction(),\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-15.0, max_x=15.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "32df2685",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The above mean function does not have any trainable parameters. It is common for a mean function to have parameters that will be set during model training. To learn more about parameters see our section on [Parameters and Their Optimisation](parameters_and_their_optimisation.ipynb)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ba43ef68",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Composition\n",
    "\n",
    "As with the kernels you can use the `+` and `*` operators to compose mean functions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "280bfd3c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For example we can add a linear to our sine wave above:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "51e6a9ce",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:42.316022Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:42.315690Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:42.901534Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:42.900792Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern12(),\n",
    "    mean_function=SineMeanFunction() + gpflow.functions.Linear(),\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-15.0, max_x=15.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "709ee9ed",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Or we can multiply the sine by a linear:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "e93fe856",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-12-02T16:10:42.904304Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-12-02T16:10:42.904059Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-12-02T16:10:43.575723Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-12-02T16:10:43.574887Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern12(),\n",
    "    mean_function=SineMeanFunction() * gpflow.functions.Linear(),\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-15.0, max_x=15.0)"
   ]
  }
